":"1310–1372","1338":"1338","1414":"1414","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1298":"1298","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Scotland","Elderslie, Renfrew, Scotland":"Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wallace","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Wallis  , especially in Scotland, where the name was introduced from the Welsh Marches by a family of tenants of the Stewarts in the 12th century.","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish (Ashkenazic) surnames, e.g.   Wallach  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walles","meanings":["English: variant of   Wallace  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Malcolm Thomas Wallace was born in 1335, in Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Adam Wallace - Laird of Elderslie and Auchinbothie, was 37 and his mother, Margaret de Lindsay, was 25. He married Lady Elizabeth Helen Baillie. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1413, in Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 78."},"et":{"1335–1413":"1335–1413","1338–1374":"1338–1374","1360–1414":"1360–1414","1298–1350":"1298–1350","1310–1372":"1310–1372","1338":"1338","1414":"1414","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1298":"1298","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","Scotland, United Kimgdom":"Scotland","Elderslie, Renfrew, Scotland":"Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Elderslie, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1335–1413":"1335–1413","1338–1374":"1338–1374","1360–1414":